data.name: Stones and Ropes - A Graph Problem
data.description:
# Stones and Ropes - A Graph Problem

You were strolling around at the beach and came across an ancient net, made out of stones tied together with ropes. As you want to figure out more about how the net is composed, you decide to pick it up by one stone and let it hang in the air. Some of the ropes will be under tension, while others will have some amount of slack. You are wondering by how much exactly any of the rope will hang below the lowest stone. 

For the sake of simplicity:
- the stones are points (meaning they have 0 diameter)
- the ropes have no thickness and are perfectly flexible, but not elastic
- you live near a very tall cliff, so even if your net is very big, you have enough space to make it hang in the air

You studied the net quite intensely already, numbered all the stones and wrote down for each two stones if they’re directly tied together by a rope and if so, how long that rope is. 

## Input format
The format in which you noted the composure of the net is by a dictionary, with each key being a stone in the net, and it’s value being a dictionary of all other stones it is directly tied to by a rope, and the appropriate rope length. 

## Task
Given this representation of the net and the stone by which you will hold the net in the air, compute the maximum amount that any rope will hang lower than the lowest stone. Output 0 if no rope hangs lower than the lowest stone. 

## Performance Requirements
The tests include nets with up to 1500 stones and some of the nets have a rope between every pair of stones. 

## Example

```
net = {‘stone_0’: {‘stone_1’: 5, ’stone_2’: 1}, 
       ‘stone_1’: {‘stone_0’: 5, ‘stone_2’: 10}, 
       ‘stone_2’: {’stone_0’: 1, ‘stone_1’: 10}}
s = ‘stone_0’
lowest_hanging_rope(net, s) = 3
```
Explanation: stone_1 will hang 5 units lower than stone_0 (s), stone_2 will hang 1 unit lower than stone_0. Thus, stone_1 is the lowest hanging stone. The rope tied between stone_1 and stone_2 with length 10 has its lowest point exactly 3 units lower than stone_1, the lowest hanging stone. 

Be aware that the lowest hanging rope is not necessarily tied to to the lowest hanging stone. Also notice that hanging the same net from a different stone will generally yield a different solution.
